Analysis of Summary Statistics¶

It is interesting to compare the mean Number of Innings that went into overtime (Inn) and cLI between the 2022 and 2023 seasons.

In 2022 the mean number of innings was 10.083333 and in 2023 it was 9.416667, meaning that there were more frequent overtime games in 2022 than 2023, implying that the games played in 2022 needed to break a tie and were closer (more competitive) games.

The mean cLI in 2022 was 1.105000 and in 2023 it was 0.548395, implying that in 2022 the Mets' games had about average importance on the team's probability of winning the World Series, and in 2023 they had a significantly less than average importance per game on the team's probability of winning the World Series.

In [18]:
#2022 times series of Met Games cLI

# cLI = Championship Leverage Index
# The importance of this game on the team's probability of winning the World Series.
# 1.0 is average importance, below 1.0 is below average importance and above 1.0 is above average importance.
# https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/NYM/2022-schedule-scores.shtml

fig = plt.subplots(figsize=(20, 5)) #set figure size

plot = sns.lineplot(data = df_22, x = df_22.Game , y = df_22.cLI)
sns.scatterplot(data = cLI_df_22, x = 'Game', y = 'cLI', color = 'red', marker = 'o', s = 100, ax = plot) #plots bottom 5 games cLI

plt.title('2022 Mets Games cLI Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Game')
plt.ylabel('cLI')
Out[18]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'cLI')

2022 Mets Games cLI Over Time (Game Number)¶

  • Around mid-season there was 1 game with the lowest attendance and there were 4 games near the end of the season that made up the bottom 5 attended games. The cLI over the 2022 season was relatively stagnant hovering around 1.0, signifying average cLI, until the end of the season where cLI dramatically increased then decreased. This indicates that the Mets' games near the end of the season were very important for their odds to win the World Series.

  • It is important to note that all bottom 5 games were away games played against PIT and MIA. Low attendance for away games is more expected than those played at home where there are more local fans.

2023 Mets Games cLI Over Time (Game Number)¶

  • There were 2 games with the lowest attendance early in the season and there were 3 games near the mid-end of the season that made up the bottom 5 attended games. The cLI over the 2023 season seems to have a strong negative relationship with time hovering around and above 1.0, signifying average and above-average cLI, until about game 60. From game 60 onwards there is a strong negative decrease in cLI, indicating that the Mets' games from about mid-season until the end of the season had very poor and improbable odds to win (/make it to) the final matchups for the World Series.

  • Similar to 2022, it is important to note that all bottom 5 games were away games. MIA games appeared again twice in the bottom 5 attended - where we can infer that NYM vs MIA games' attendees prefer to not attend these games. This also implies that there are perhaps not many Mets' fans in Miami, where these games are played. Again, low attendance for away games is more expected than those played at home where there are more local fans.

  • Because of the negative slope in 2023, the following analyses will be a correlation matrix analysis of numeric variables.

plt.legend(title = 'Win/Loss')
plt.show()

2022 & 2023 Swarmplots of NYM's Win/Loss vs Attendance¶

  • For both 2022 and 2023, there were slightly more losses than wins for the NYM when there were very high attended games (about 45,000+ attendees). In 2022: 2 games were won and 4 were lost and in 2023: 2 games were won and 3 were lost for these very high attended games.

  • In 2022, there is a high volume of wins concentrated around mid-high attended games (about 35,000 - 38,000 attendees). While in 2023 the spread of the swarm between wins and losses is closer to an equal amount overall.

  • At a glance, there were more overall wins in 2022 than 2023. In both years there was an equal amount of win-walk-offs (6), but a higher number of loss-walk-offs in 2023 (increasing from 3 to 6 games L-wo).

2022 & 2023 Count of NYM's Wins/Losses for Home and Away Games¶

  • As predicted, across both years there are more wins than losses at home games, where the NYM are more comfortable playing (and have more fans supporting them in the stands).

  • Though in 2022, the opposite is not true for away games, where more games were actually won than lost - thus indicating an overall better performing season. While in 2023, significantly more games were lost than won at away games.

  • Additionally, for 2023, there is not a major increase between games won and lost at home - when games won at home in 2022 were roughly double the games lost at home.
